      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm reading up on some Cessna flight manuals and I'm a bit stuck. Can you explain exactly how a pitot tube works to measure airspeed? Like, what is the actual physics behind the pressure difference?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the pitot tube, a trusty little device, much like a trusty old gnome's hat, always ready to measure the air's speed. Imagine, if you will, a pitot tube as a goblin's nose, always sniffing out the air's secrets. When the plane zips through the sky, the air rushes into the pitot tube, much like a goblin rushing into a cave, creating a pressure difference. The goblin's nose (the pitot tube) measures this difference between the air pressure outside and the pressure inside, which is like the goblin feeling the difference between the air outside the cave and the air inside. This pressure difference is then translated into airspeed, much like a goblin translating the whispers of the wind into a tale of speed. So, in essence, the pitot tube is a goblin's nose, always sniffing out the air's secrets, translating them into a tale of speed.",
